[[File:Kamikura-jinja03s2048.jpg|thumb|160px|Torii at the base of the stone steps]]
Kamikura Shrine is located on {{ill|Chihogamine|ja|千穂ヶ峯|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chihogamine|qq=}}, a peak of Kamikura Mountain (神倉山), standing 120 meters tall. Access to the shrine requires climbing 538 steep stone steps, said to have been built during the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamakura period|qq=}} by the patronage of {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoritomo|qq=}}.

The shrine's main sacred object is Gotobiki Rock, a giant boulder venerated as a {{ill|Shintai|ja|神体|1=Shintai|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shintai|13=User:Immanuelle/Shintai|qq=}}. Excavations around the rock have uncovered ancient relics, including pieces of {{ill|dōtaku|ja|銅鐸|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/dōtaku|qq=}}, indicating the site's origin in {{ill|Iwakura (Shinto)|ja|磐座|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwakura (Shinto)|qq=}} worship.<ref name="Kadokawa_1985_294">"Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten" Editorial Committee, 1985, p. 294</ref>

According to {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojiki|qq=}} and {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}, this location is associated with the legendary {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Jimmu|qq=}}, who received divine guidance from the god Takakuraji while traversing this area during his Eastern Expedition.<ref>{{Cite book |translator=[[Ujiya Tsutomu]] |title=Nihon Shoki (Modern Translation) |year=1988 |publisher=[[Kōdansha]] |series=[[Kodansha Academic Library]] |isbn=4-06-158833-8 |page=94}}</ref>

== History ==
The site became prominent as part of the {{ill|Kumano faith|ja|熊野信仰|1=Kumano Three Shrines|lt=Kumano faith|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano faith|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Three Shrines|qq=}}, believed to be the first place where the {{ill|Kumano Gongen|ja|熊野権現|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Gongen|qq=}} deities descended. This belief reinforced its status as a spiritual center and part of the Kumano Sanzan complex.<ref name="Heibon_1997_191">Heibonsha, 1997, p. 191</ref>

The shrine has suffered multiple disasters over centuries, including fires during the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sengoku period|qq=}}, with subsequent reconstructions supported by both the {{ill|Tokugawa clan|ja|徳川家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa clan|qq=}} and local feudal lords.<ref>Shingū City, 1984, p. 971</ref> It was incorporated into the Kumano Hayatama Taisha in {{ill|1907|ja|1907th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1907|qq=}} during the state-led modernization of religious institutions.<ref>Shingū City Education Committee, 1990, p. 30</ref>

== Cultural Properties ==

=== National Historic Site ===
The Kamikura Shrine precincts are part of the designated {{ill|Kumano Sanzan|ja|熊野三山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Sanzan|qq=}} National Historic Site and the UNESCO World Heritage Site "Sacred Sites and Pilgrimage Routes in the Kii Mountain Range."<ref>{{Cite book ja-jp|author=World Heritage Promotion Council of the Three Prefectures|year=2005|title=World Heritage Sites of the Kii Mountain Range|publisher=Council of Wakayama, Nara, and Mie Prefectures}}</ref>

=== Wakayama Prefecture Designated Historic Site ===
The 538-step stone staircase and a nearby "Shimogawa" marker stone are recognized as prefectural historic landmarks. These features highlight the region's cultural significance and the historical Kumano pilgrimage routes.<ref>Wakayama Prefecture Cultural Property Guide</ref>

=== Local Cultural Properties ===
Three relics within the precincts, including the shrine's hand-washing basin and a stone vessel, are designated as local cultural properties.<ref>Shingū City Cultural Heritage Report, 1990</ref>

== Oto Matsuri ==
{{See|Oto Matsuri}}
The {{ill|Oto Matsuri|ja|御燈祭|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Oto Matsuri|qq=}} is an annual fire festival held on February 6th, featuring men carrying torches down the steep stone steps of the shrine in an exhilarating spectacle. The origins of this festival are linked to myths of Emperor [[Jimmu's Eastern Expedition]].<ref name=moriyasu>{{Cite journal|author=Moriyasu Toshihisa |date=2011-03 |url=https://uuair.repo.nii.ac.jp/records/4572 |title=The "Fire Festival" in Nakagawa Kenji's Works |journal=Journal of Utsunomiya University Faculty of Education |pages=17-28}}</ref>

== Access ==
The shrine is accessible by:
* {{ill|JR Kisei Main Line|ja|紀勢本線|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/JR Kisei Main Line|qq=}}: From {{ill|Shingū Station|ja|新宮駅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shingū Station|qq=}}, it is a 15-minute walk or a short ride by {{ill|Kumano Kotsu|ja|熊野交通|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Kotsu|qq=}} bus to the "Court Office" stop.

