The '''Kamikura Shrine''' (神倉神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in {{ill|Shingū, Wakayama|ja|新宮市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shingū, Wakayama|qq=}}, Japan. It is a subordinate shrine of the {{ill|Kumano Hayatama Taisha|ja|熊野速玉大社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Hayatama Taisha|qq=}}, part of the {{ill|Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano Sanzan|ja|熊野三山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Sanzan|qq=}} complex. The shrine is designated as a National Historic Site under the {{ill|Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano Sanzan|ja|熊野三山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Sanzan|qq=}} and is included in the UNESCO World Heritage Site {{ill|Sacred Sites and Pilgrimage Routes in the Kii Mountain Range|ja|紀伊山地の霊場と参詣道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sacred Sites and Pilgrimage Routes in the Kii Mountain Range|qq=}}.

== Sacred Rock Worship Shrine ==

[[File:Kamikura-jinja03s2048.jpg|thumb|160px|Torii at the base of the stone steps]]
Kamikura Shrine is located on {{ill|Chihogamine|ja|千穂ヶ峯|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chihogamine|qq=}}, a peak of Kamikura Mountain (神倉山), standing 120 meters tall. Access to the shrine requires climbing 538 steep stone steps, said to have been built during the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamakura period|qq=}} by the patronage of {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼朝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoritomo|qq=}}.

The shrine's main sacred object is Gotobiki Rock, a giant boulder venerated as a {{ill|Shintai|ja|神体|1=Shintai|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shintai|13=User:Immanuelle/Shintai|qq=}}. Excavations around the rock have uncovered ancient relics, including pieces of {{ill|dōtaku|ja|銅鐸|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/dōtaku|qq=}}, indicating the site's origin in {{ill|Iwakura rock|lt=Iwakura rock|lt=Iwakura (Shinto)|ja|磐座|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwakura (Shinto)|qq=}} worship.<ref name="Kadokawa_1985_294">"Kadokawa Nihon Chimei Daijiten" Editorial Committee, 1985, p. 294</ref>

According to {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojiki|qq=}} and {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}, this location is associated with the legendary {{ill|Emperor Jimmu|ja|神武天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Jimmu|qq=}}, who received divine guidance from the god Takakuraji while traversing this area during his Eastern Expedition.<ref>{{Cite book |translator=[[Ujiya Tsutomu]] |title=Nihon Shoki (Modern Translation) |year=1988 |publisher=[[Kōdansha]] |series=[[Kodansha Academic Library]] |isbn=4-06-158833-8 |page=94}}</ref>

== History ==
The site became prominent as part of the {{ill|Kumano faith|ja|熊野信仰|1=Kumano shrine|lt=Kumano Three Shrines|lt=Kumano faith|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano faith|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Three Shrines|qq=}}, believed to be the first place where the {{ill|Kumano Gongen|ja|熊野権現|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumano Gongen|qq=}} deities descended. This belief reinforced its status as a spiritual center and part of the Kumano Sanzan complex.<ref name="Heibon_1997_191">Heibonsha, 1997, p. 191</ref>

The shrine has suffered multiple disasters over centuries, including fires during the {{ill|Sengoku period|ja|戦国時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sengoku period|qq=}}, with subsequent reconstructions supported by both the {{ill|Tokugawa clan|ja|徳川家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa clan|qq=}} and local feudal lords.<ref>Shingū City, 1984, p. 971</ref> It was incorporated into the Kumano Hayatama Taisha in {{ill|1907|ja|1907年|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1907|qq=}} during the state-led modernization of religious institutions.<ref>Shingū City Education Committee, 1990, p. 30</ref>

== Cultural Properties ==

